dataIdInfo.envirDesc: Microsoft Windows 7 Version 6.1 (Build 7601) Service Pack 1; Esri ArcGIS 10.5.0.6491
dataIdInfo.idPurp:
Feature class contains structures inside and adjacent to funded parks. The feature class servers two functions.
1) Help give context to the site. Sponsor representatives discuss a project site relative to civic buildings in the vicinity. Additionally, 6(f)3 maps often can only be interpreted based on the locations of civic buildings depicted in the map.
2) Help describe an strange statuses of non-recreation structure inside of the 6(f)3 boundary. Some buildings pre-date the original LWCF or ANCRC projects. LWCF does not have a grandfathering policy but it is generally policy to not pursue compliance issues relating to pre-existing structures. Some project map ambiguous about if the structure is included or not. Additionally, the National Park Service issues waivers for structures.
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
label – identifies the primary function of the structure such as town hall or fire station. This field is intended to be used for labeling in ArcGIS.

type – indicates if the feature’s relationship to 6(f)3. The values are as follows

  • active conversion – Some kind of structure that is or has been identified as a conversion. Many of these are minor and are not being pursued because of that.

  • not documented – There is no information in any of the project files on the status of the structure. Additionally, a timeline of aerial imagery going back to the 1900s is not able to help determine its status. There is no documentation

  • NPS Waiver – The National Park Service has waived structure. Its use has been explicitly allowed inside of the 6(f)3 boundary.

  • Outside 6(f)3 – A structure that is outside of the 6(f)3 boundary. It is being kept inside of the dataset for context around the park site

  • Pre-existing – structure existed before the first grant on the site.

  • Recreation – structure that is in direct support of recreation

  • Unclear inclusion – The project boundary map is very ambiguous. It is not clear if the structure is inside of the 6(f)3 boundary or not.

  • Unknown – no information about the structure. Possibility not even sure if it is a structure.

structType – indicates if the structure is in support of outdoor recreation like a community center or senior center or if the site does not directly support outdoor recreation like town halls and fire stations.

  • non-support – structure such as a fire station, or town hall which does not directly support outdoor recreation.

  • Recreation – a structure that directly provides a recreation opportunity

  • Support – a structure that is considered to be in directly support according to the national park service. This includes community centers, senior centers, boys and girls clubs, and public libraries.

  • Unknown – do not have enough information to place the structure inside of a category.

docYear – The year on the document from which this structure was digitized from

projectNum – the project number related to the document where the structure was described

source – indicates the source where the structure information was found in

note1 – notes about the land use or structure

note2 – continued notes about the land use or structure

CALC_ACRE – The accessed acres according to project documents, deeds, appraisals, project contracts, correspondence, and other documentation.

ACRE_AREA – the assessed acres of the property, which come from deeds and project documents.

Maintenance instructions

Please add and change buildings as you become aware of them. Keeping proper track of these structures helps avoid drama from a possible conversion because we know if structures are preexisting, or waived.

Coordinate system is NAD_1983_UTM_Zone_15N
